Such an implementation seems incorrect. I guess two queues are considered equal if they contains the same elements, e.g.
```
   concurrent_queue<int> q1, q2;
   q1.push(1);
   q2.push(1);
   bool expect_true = (q1 == q2);
```

`q1` and `q2` both contains only one element equal to `1`, so these queues are considered equal. But they does not point to the same representation, so your implementation of `operator==` would return `false`. I believe that we should not have the case when two queues points to the same representation - it can lean in double-free problems.

